1778282138818242	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykg0		item.create	bn-103k	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nAfter `maw ws merge` advances the epoch, bn-3vf5's auto-rebase-siblings advances each non-target workspace's HEAD ref but explicitly does NOT update its worktree (`mutate_worktree: false` at `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/auto_rebase.rs:253`). The intent was to avoid clobbering uncommitted user edits.\n\nConsequences in the field:\n1. `git status` in a sibling worktree shows phantom `M` modifications for every file the rebase changed, because HEAD's blobs differ from the worktree's stale blobs.\n2. The next `maw ws sync` on that sibling sees \"uncommitted changes\" via `workspace_has_uncommitted_changes()` (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/checks.rs:70-86`) and refuses with the dirty-workspace guard.\n3. `auto_sync_if_stale()` (`crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/mod.rs:388-494`) bails for the same reason at line 474-481 — it cannot distinguish \"user has real edits\" from \"worktree is just stale post-auto-rebase.\"\n4. Workaround in the field: `git stash push` per sibling before `maw ws sync`. With many siblings this is per-workspace ceremony that erases the auto-rebase ergonomics win.\n\nGoal\n----\nWhen auto-rebase-siblings runs against a sibling whose worktree is clean at the moment of rebase, ALSO update the worktree to match the rebased HEAD. Skip rules already gate on dirty workspaces; if we got past them, the worktree is provably clean and a checkout is safe.\n\nDesign\n------\n- `auto_rebase.rs` already runs the dirty check under-lock as a skip rule. If we pass that rule, the worktree is clean.\n- Change the call to `rebase_workspace_run` in `auto_rebase.rs:253` (or its surrounding orchestration) to set `mutate_worktree: true` for the siblings that pass all skip rules.\n- The existing `sync_worktree_to_epoch()` in `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/checks.rs:95-159` is the right primitive; it already does `git checkout --detach <epoch>` after a clean-worktree precondition.\n- The dirty re-check must remain UNDER the lock so we don't race with an agent who modifies the worktree between the skip check and the checkout.\n- If for any reason the worktree-update step fails (e.g. transient I/O, a fresh dirty file appearing), do NOT abort the merge or roll back the ref advance. Log \"skipped worktree update\" for the sibling and let the user run `maw ws sync` manually. The Prime Invariant holds — refs are advanced, no work lost.\n\nPer-sibling result categories (extend the existing set):\n- \"rebased clean (worktree synced)\"\n- \"rebased clean (worktree unchanged: dirty)\"  ← the case we currently land in for ALL siblings\n- \"rebased with N conflicts (worktree synced)\"\n- \"rebased with N conflicts (worktree unchanged: dirty)\"\n\nNote on conflicted rebases: when the rebase produces conflict markers, those markers ARE part of the rebased HEAD's tree. Checking the worktree out to the rebased HEAD writes those markers to disk, which is consistent with the conflict-as-data model — `maw ws resolve` sees the markers and proceeds normally.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/auto_rebase.rs:230-281` — flip `mutate_worktree` to true conditional on skip rules; surface result-category extension.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs` — `rebase_workspace_run` already accepts `mutate_worktree` per the bn-3vf5 refactor; verify the worktree path is sound when called from auto-rebase context.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/checks.rs:95-159` — `sync_worktree_to_epoch` may already cover this; verify reusability.\n- CHANGELOG.md.\n\nBackward compat\n---------------\nThis is a behavior change for users who relied on \"siblings show modified files until I sync them\" as a signal. After this change, post-merge siblings look clean. Document in CHANGELOG.\n\nTests\n-----\n- 3-workspace batch where two siblings are clean and one is dirty:\n  - Clean siblings end at clean worktree on new HEAD (no `M` files in `git status`).\n  - Dirty sibling stays at old worktree, refs advanced (today's behavior — preserved).\n- Sibling worktree contains conflict markers after rebase: worktree is updated, markers visible, `maw ws resolve --list` finds them.\n- Race: simulate dirty-file appearance between skip check and checkout — the worktree update is skipped (logged), parent merge succeeds, refs are advanced.\n- Existing `tests/auto_rebase_siblings.rs` updated to reflect new defaults.\n\nRisks\n-----\n- Stale `target/` build artifacts in the sibling worktree are NOT files maw tracks; checkout doesn't touch them. Verify with a test using `cargo build` artifacts in a sibling.\n- An agent has the sibling's worktree open in an editor: the editor may show \"file changed on disk\" warnings. Acceptable — the agent's commits are not lost (refs advanced).\n- LFS-tracked files: confirm the existing `sync_worktree_to_epoch` path handles LFS smudge correctly.\n\nSize\n----\nM — small code change, but careful concurrency surface and test matrix.","kind":"task","labels":["ux","merge","sync","ergonomics","followup-bn-3vf5"],"size":"m","title":"Auto-rebase siblings should sync clean worktrees, not just refs"}	blake3:QY5SGWcozmnbjfq1vkXXeP2xsTyeZm_KekiNaRAAxvs
1778282186342877	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEykw0		item.create	bn-3mbj	{"description":"Problem (high severity — silent partial work loss)\n--------------------------------------------------\nWhen `maw ws sync --rebase` produces a structured conflict on a file, `maw ws resolve <ws> --keep <ws>` is documented to \"keep the workspace's side.\" In practice it writes the workspace's PRE-REBASE blob directly to the worktree, deleting any changes that landed in the new epoch from sibling workspaces.\n\nReported case (still valid against current main):\n- bn-2i4y merges to main with a 377-line wiring change in `scrub.rs`.\n- bn-2ghz is rebased onto the new main and produces a structured conflict on `scrub.rs` because its commits also touched the file.\n- `maw ws resolve bn-2ghz --keep bn-2ghz` writes bn-2ghz's pre-rebase `scrub.rs`, silently deleting the 377 lines of bn-2i4y's already-merged wiring.\n- Reporter would have shipped broken code if they hadn't manually inspected.\n\nThis is a Prime-Invariant-adjacent regression: the work isn't lost from refs (bn-2i4y's commit is still on main), but the post-resolve worktree drops it, and a subsequent `git add -A && git commit` re-introduces a regression that looks like an authored deletion.\n\nRoot cause (verified in code)\n-----------------------------\n`ConflictSide` (`crates/maw-core/src/model/conflict.rs:99-122`) stores only `(workspace, content blob OID, timestamp, mode)`. The \"workspace side\" blob written into the sidecar is the workspace's pre-rebase HEAD's version of the file (set in `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:901, 1191`). When `--keep <ws-name>` is invoked, `resolve_structured.rs:534-547` reads that blob and writes it directly to the worktree.\n\nThree-way merge for clean overlaps DOES exist — `try_clean_three_way_overlap()` at `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:1003-1045` correctly diff3-merges `(base_blob, epoch_blob, workspace_blob)` and uses the result when no conflict surfaces. But the moment a textual conflict appears, the three-way is bypassed and only the raw blobs are stored. `--keep <ws>` then becomes a wholesale revert.\n\nGoal\n----\n`--keep <ws>` should preserve the workspace's INTENT applied to the new epoch — semantically: \"take the diff between the merge base and the workspace, and apply it on top of the new epoch's content, with the workspace winning on conflicts.\"\n\nDesign\n------\n1. Extend `ConflictSide` (or the conflict-tree sidecar format) to include the BASE blob OID (the merge base used during rebase). `try_clean_three_way_overlap` already has access to it; conflict creation paths at `rebase.rs:874, 901, 1191` need to thread it through. Field name: `base_content: Option<GitOid>` with `#[serde(default, skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")]` for forward/backward compat.\n2. Change `--keep <ws-name>` resolution at `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/resolve_structured.rs:534-547`:\n   - If both `base_content` and the epoch side are present, run `merge_text(base, epoch, workspace, \"epoch\", \"base\", ws_name)` (the same primitive `try_clean_three_way_overlap` uses), with `ws` as the favoured side on internal conflicts.\n   - Strategy: there's no built-in \"ours-wins\" three-way in `merge_text` today — verify via reading. If absent, add a thin variant that resolves diff3-internal conflicts by taking the named side.\n   - Fallback (no base in sidecar — old workspaces, or a code path that didn't store base): preserve current behavior (write workspace blob) but emit a single-line stderr WARNING: `\"warning: --keep <ws> is using legacy blob-replace semantics; sibling content from main may be dropped. To verify: maw exec <ws> -- git diff HEAD~1 <path>\"`.\n3. `--keep epoch` and `--keep both` semantics: epoch-side resolution is unaffected (the epoch blob already contains sibling-merged content). `--keep both` (concatenation) also unaffected — both sides are preserved literally.\n4. Resolution success messaging: when a three-way merge completes, print `resolved: <path> (3-way merge: ws intent on top of epoch)` so the user knows the resolution was non-trivial.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-core/src/model/conflict.rs:99-122` — extend `ConflictSide` with `base_content`.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/rebase.rs:874, 901, 1191` — thread base blob into conflict creation.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/resolve_structured.rs:225-350, 473-550` — change `--keep <ws>` resolution path.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/resolve.rs:99-289` — verify legacy fallback path matches.\n- `crates/maw-core/src/merge/types.rs:374` — `ConflictTree` shape if surface needs adjustment.\n- Tests for the regression case.\n\nBackward compat\n---------------\n- Sidecars without `base_content` still resolve via the current path with a stderr warning. New rebases produce sidecars with base.\n- Migration on first `maw ws sync` after install — none required; new field is optional.\n\nTests\n-----\nUnit:\n- Three-way merge with workspace intent additive to epoch: result includes both.\n- Three-way merge with workspace deleting a line that epoch also modified: workspace wins (ws-favoured) and the resolution preserves the deletion at the workspace's chosen position.\n- Sidecar without `base_content`: legacy path used, warning emitted.\n\nIntegration (the reported regression):\n- Setup: workspace A modifies file F lines 1-10, merges. Workspace B (forked from before A) modifies F lines 50-60. Rebase B onto post-A main.\n- B's rebase produces a conflict on F (because A and B both touched the file).\n- `maw ws resolve B --keep B` produces a worktree with BOTH A's lines 1-10 changes AND B's lines 50-60 changes — not just B's pre-rebase content.\n- Symmetric test for `--keep epoch` (no behavior change expected).\n\nProperty test:\n- Random pairs of additive edits to disjoint regions of a file → `--keep <ws>` always preserves both.\n- Random conflicting edits → ws side wins on overlap, epoch preserved elsewhere.\n\nRisks\n-----\n- The internal \"ws-wins\" diff3 strategy must be deterministic and well-tested — wrong tie-breaking could itself become a quiet data-loss path.\n- `merge_text` is in shared code (used by `try_clean_three_way_overlap` already). Changing it risks breaking other callers; prefer adding a new variant.\n- LFS-tracked files: blobs are LFS pointers, three-way merging is over the pointer not the content. Existing behavior; document as out of scope.\n\nSize\n----\nL — sidecar format change, semantic core change, broad test surface, plus a real correctness story. Allocate review time for the merge-strategy variant before implementing.\n\nPriority\n--------\nURGENT. This is silent partial work loss. Reporter caught it manually; future invocations may not. File at top of queue.","kind":"bug","labels":["correctness","data-loss","resolve","merge"],"size":"l","title":"maw ws resolve --keep <ws> must preserve workspace intent, not pre-rebase blob","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:JMkWj25hDQfzX9gIq_xBULHdEDBAYuS1pTY9BPcvzoY
1778282217017308	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEylA0		item.create	bn-sgm8	{"description":"Problem\n-------\nA user reported reaching for `git show <commit>:<path>` to retrieve content from a destroyed workspace because they didn't realize `maw ws recover --show <path>` exists. The functionality is good — it's a discoverability gap.\n\nVerified surface (`maw ws recover --help` and `maw ws recover bn-11ip` both expose rich features):\n- `maw ws recover` — list destroyed workspaces (table)\n- `maw ws recover <name>` — destroy history with `Next:` hints (good)\n- `maw ws recover <name> --show <path>` — print file content from latest snapshot\n- `maw ws recover --search <pattern>` — search across pinned snapshots\n- `maw ws recover <name> --to <new>` — restore as new workspace\n- `maw ws recover --ref <ref> ...` — operate on a specific recovery ref\n\nGaps\n----\n1. **List view has no \"Next:\" footer.** The single-workspace view (`maw ws recover <name>`) ends with hint text. The list view (`maw ws recover` with no arg) doesn't, so users see a table and assume that's all there is.\n2. **No file-level restore-to-worktree.** `--show <path>` prints content; `--to <new>` restores the whole workspace. There's no `maw ws recover <name> --restore-file <path>` to copy a single file from the snapshot back into the current workspace's worktree. Users currently `--show > path` manually.\n3. **Capture-mode `none` is opaque.** When the destroy record shows `capture: none`, users assume \"nothing to recover\" and reach for raw git. In reality, \"none\" means \"all work was already merged at destroy time\" — the data is on the merged branch, not in a recovery ref. The list output should explain this with a hint, not just print `none` and an empty SNAPSHOT column.\n\nGoal\n----\nClose the discoverability gap with three small fixes.\n\nDesign\n------\n1. **Add a `Next:` footer to the list view.** After the table, print:\n   ```\n   Next: maw ws recover <name>          # show destroy history for one\n         maw ws recover <name> --show <path>    # show a file\n         maw ws recover --search <pattern>      # search across snapshots\n   ```\n   File: `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/recover.rs:54-108` (the list-output function).\n\n2. **Add `--restore-file <path>`.** Copies the named path from the snapshot into the current default workspace's worktree.\n   - `maw ws recover <name> --restore-file <path>` — uses latest snapshot.\n   - `maw ws recover --ref <ref> --restore-file <path>` — uses specific ref.\n   - Refuses if the destination path already has uncommitted changes (unless `--force`); prints `restored: <path>` and a one-line hint to commit.\n   - Implementation: read blob at the recovery ref's tree, write to disk path; preserves mode bits.\n\n3. **Capture-mode `none` hint.** In the list output, when `capture: none`, change the SNAPSHOT column to render `-` AND append a footnote line: `* \"none\" capture: work was already merged when destroyed; check git log on the merge target.` Keep the table itself terse.\n\nFiles affected\n--------------\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/recover.rs:54-108` — list output footer + capture-none footnote.\n- `crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/recover.rs:245-+` — add `--restore-file` flag and handler. Reuse the same ref-resolution path used by `--show`.\n- The clap definition for `maw ws recover`.\n- Tests under `tests/destroy_recover.rs` and `tests/recovery_capture.rs`.\n\nTests\n-----\n- `--restore-file` with valid path → file written, mode preserved.\n- `--restore-file` with non-existent path in snapshot → error with available paths hint.\n- `--restore-file` with destination dirty → refuses, suggests `--force`.\n- `--restore-file --force` overrides safely.\n- List output footer present when at least one destroyed workspace exists.\n- Capture-none footnote appears when any row has `capture: none` and not otherwise.\n\nBackward compat\n---------------\n- List output gains lines; consumers that parse the table head/rows are unaffected as long as the column structure is preserved.\n- New flag `--restore-file` is purely additive.\n\nSize\n----\nS — small surface, mostly UX polish and one new flag.\n\nOpen question (not blocking)\n----------------------------\nShould `maw ws recover <name>` (no flags) also emit the `--restore-file` hint in its `Next:` block? Probably yes; cheap and consistent.","kind":"task","labels":["ux","recover","ergonomics"],"size":"s","title":"Improve maw ws recover discoverability and add file-level restore"}	blake3:2wqt_vEgbsJKbVor9xkbKD1-o6Kwq73QwYfzPIqep10
